# Language
default: EN
user_notes: JA allowed

# ctxledger Development Housekeeping

- These `last_session.md` rules apply only when developing `ctxledger` itself.
- When a new `ctxledger` development session starts, read `last_session.md` first.
- When a `ctxledger` development work loop is done, update `last_session.md` with a concise continuation note for the next session.
- Keep the git repository up-to-date with descriptive commits.
- Ignore the status of `.gitignore`.
- When developing `ctxledger` itself, the general agent workflow rules below also apply in addition to this housekeeping section.

# General Agent Workflow Rules for Repositories Using ctxledger

- Use `ctxledger` as the canonical system of record for workflow progress, resumability, projection state, and durable memory.
- Treat repository notes, resume artifacts, and local continuation files as auxiliary or derived context unless the repository explicitly defines them as canonical for some narrower purpose.
- Favor reliable resumability and useful future recall over minimal logging. A slightly more explicit operational trail is better than an ambiguous one.

## Workspace and workflow lifecycle

- At the beginning of work, ensure the current repository is tracked in `ctxledger`:
  - register or confirm the workspace with `workspace_register`
  - if the task appears to continue existing work, prefer resuming existing work before starting anything new
  - use `workflow_start` only when the work is genuinely new or when no corresponding active workflow can be resumed
- Be explicit about identifier types and never substitute one for another:
  - `workspace_register` returns a `workspace_id`, not a `workflow_instance_id`
  - `workflow_start` returns a `workflow_instance_id` and an `attempt_id`
  - `workflow_resume` requires a `workflow_instance_id`
  - `workflow_checkpoint` and `workflow_complete` require both `workflow_instance_id` and `attempt_id`
- Before calling `workflow_resume`, verify that the identifier came from:
  - a prior `workflow_start` result
  - a prior `workflow_resume` result
  - workflow-oriented stored context that explicitly labels it as `workflow_instance_id`
- Never pass a `workspace_id` to `workflow_resume`.
- If you only know a `workspace_id`, do not guess a workflow identifier:
  - recover the active or latest workflow through available canonical workflow context first
  - if no resumable workflow can be identified, start a new workflow instead of fabricating an id
- If a resume-oriented tool call fails or times out, do not blindly retry the same malformed request:
  - first re-check that the id type is correct
  - then distinguish whether the problem appears to be identifier misuse, missing workflow state, or runtime/server degradation
- When deciding between resume and start:
  - prefer reusing an existing workflow when the task objective, repository, or recent work context clearly matches ongoing work
  - avoid creating duplicate workflows for the same task just because context is incomplete
  - if uncertain, try to recover or inspect existing workflow state first, then start a new workflow only if needed
  - only treat a workflow as resumable when it is still operationally open; terminal workflows should be inspected, not continued
  - prefer workspace-scoped discovery or inspection flows when you only know the repository/workspace context; prefer `workflow_resume` only when you already have a confirmed `workflow_instance_id`
- During work, record meaningful progress with `workflow_checkpoint`, especially after:
  - planning or narrowing the task
  - identifying a root cause or important technical decision
  - completing a code change
  - adding or updating tests
  - finishing validation or debugging steps
  - reaching a blocker, ambiguity, or handoff point
- Each checkpoint should make future resumption easier. Include, when possible:
  - what changed
  - what was learned or confirmed
  - what remains to do
  - the next intended action
  - current verification status
  - any blocker, risk, or open question
- Use verification-related workflow fields when they meaningfully reflect the current state of the work.
- Treat `workflow_complete` as a terminal transition, not as a general "save progress" operation.
- Terminal workflow states include:
  - `completed`
  - `failed`
  - `cancelled`
- Once a workflow is terminal, do not attempt to add more checkpoints to it.
- If more work may still occur in the current work loop, prefer another `workflow_checkpoint` and delay `workflow_complete` until the work is truly done.
- If new work appears after a workflow has already become terminal, start a new workflow instead of trying to continue the closed one.
- Do not silently skip workflow recording just because the task is small. Short tasks still benefit from start/checkpoint/complete discipline when they are part of tracked work.
- If workflow operations fail:
  - do not ignore the failure silently
  - make a reasonable attempt to understand and retry when appropriate
  - if the failure persists, continue work only with explicit awareness that workflow state is degraded or incomplete
  - surface the workflow-recording problem in your status reporting
- When the task or work loop is done:
  - mark the workflow as finished with `workflow_complete`
  - keep the git repository up-to-date with a descriptive commit if code or tracked files changed
  - leave enough context for the next session to understand what was completed and what remains

## Memory tool usage

- Use memory tools when they can materially improve continuity, recall, or decision quality. Do not treat them as mandatory on every small step, but do treat them as part of normal tracked work.
- Early in a session, or before making an important decision, consider using `memory_get_context` to retrieve relevant supporting context for:
  - the current workflow
  - the current workspace
  - the current ticket or task
- Treat `memory_get_context` as a hierarchy-aware, route-explainable tool, not as a flat episode lookup.
- Read structured fields before summarizing:
  - `summary_selection_applied`
  - `summary_selection_kind`
  - `memory_context_groups`
  - `retrieval_routes_present`
  - `primary_retrieval_routes_present`
  - `auxiliary_retrieval_routes_present`
  - `retrieval_route_presence`
  - `retrieval_route_group_counts`
  - `retrieval_route_item_counts`
  - `summary_first_has_episode_groups`
  - `summary_first_is_summary_only`
  - `summary_first_child_episode_count`
  - `summary_first_child_episode_ids`
  - `primary_episode_groups_present_after_query_filter`
  - `auxiliary_only_after_query_filter`
- Use `memory_context_groups` as the primary hierarchy-aware output when structure matters.
- Treat flat compatibility fields as supporting output unless the repository later redefines them as canonical.
- Read retrieval routes literally:
  - `summary_first` = primary summary-selected path
  - `episode_direct` = direct visible episode path
  - `workspace_inherited_auxiliary` = inherited workspace auxiliary context
  - `relation_supports_auxiliary` = relation-derived auxiliary context
  - `graph_summary_auxiliary` = derived graph-backed auxiliary summary-member context
- Never treat `graph_summary_auxiliary` as canonical truth.
- Read summary state as canonical-relational first; read graph-backed summary enrichment as derived and degradable.
- If `summary_first_has_episode_groups = true`, read the result as summary + episode primary output.
- If `summary_first_is_summary_only = true`, read the result as summary-only primary output, not as auxiliary-only output.
- If `include_episodes = false`, read only the fields and grouped routes that are actually present; do not assume hidden summary-first placeholders.
- If source matters, use route metadata explicitly instead of inferring from returned text.
- Interpret:
  - `summary_selection_kind = "memory_summary_first"` as canonical summary-first selection
  - `summary_selection_kind = "episode_summary_first"` as episode-derived summary fallback
- Use `memory_search` when:
  - similar work may already have been done before
  - you need to recall prior failures, tradeoffs, or debugging outcomes
  - you want to reuse a previous implementation pattern, operating decision, or recovery approach
- Use `memory_remember_episode` when the current work produces knowledge that is likely to help future sessions, such as:
  - a non-obvious root cause
  - an important design or operational decision
  - a reusable debugging or validation pattern
  - a failure mode and its recovery steps
  - a workflow/process lesson worth preserving
- Prefer storing fewer, higher-signal memory episodes over noisy repetition.
- When recording an episode, write it so that a future agent can understand:
  - what happened
  - why it mattered
  - how to apply the lesson later

## Change sizing and semantic decomposition

- Keep generated code, tests, and documentation semantically small.
- Prefer one clear behavior change, one narrow refactor, or one focused documentation update per slice.
- Split large work into small semantic slices that can be reviewed, tested, and resumed independently.
- Avoid mixing unrelated concerns in the same change, even if they are close together in the codebase.
- For tests, prefer focused scenarios with a single assertion theme over large multi-purpose test cases.
- For documentation, prefer short topic-focused sections over broad mixed updates.
- If a task is too large to keep semantically small, first define the sub-slices, then implement them incrementally.

## Agent behavior expectations

- Prefer explicit state transitions over implicit assumptions.
- Prefer recoverability over brevity when the two are in tension.
- When in doubt, leave enough workflow and memory context that another capable agent could continue the work with minimal ambiguity.
- Prefer structured MCP/tool fields over brief human-readable status messages when both are present.
- If a workflow-completion result includes `auto_memory_details`, inspect it before summarizing what happened.
- If `auto_memory_details.summary_build` is present, treat it as the authoritative explanation of summary automation.
- Read at least:
  - `summary_build_attempted`
  - `summary_build_succeeded`
  - `summary_build_requested`
  - `summary_build_status`
  - `summary_build_skipped_reason`
  - `summary_build_trigger`
  - `summary_build_scope`
  - `summary_build_replace_existing`
  - `summary_build_replaced_existing_summary`
  - `built_memory_summary_id`
  - `built_summary_membership_count`
- Do not compress structured outcomes into vague statements like â€śauto memory ranâ€ť or â€śsummary was builtâ€ť.
- Treat workflow-summary automation as:
  - explicit
  - checkpoint-gated
  - non-fatal
- Read policy metadata literally:
  - `default_requested = false`
  - `request_field = latest_checkpoint.checkpoint_json.build_episode_summary`
  - `trigger = latest_checkpoint.build_episode_summary_true`
- Keep these facts separate:
  - auto-memory recorded
  - summary build attempted
  - summary build succeeded
